January 4, 2021 | https://www.talkinghightech.com/en/full-stack-interview-sum-function/ | <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/*/https://www.talkinghightech.com/en/full-stack-interview-sum-function/">archive.org</a>
<br/><!-- hnss:readable-content --><hr/><div id="readability-page-1" class="page"><div><p>Continuing our Hacking the <a aria-label="interview series (opens in a new tab)" href="https://www.talkinghightech.com/en/category/javascript-interview/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">interview series</a> with this continuous sum function interview question in javascript.</p><p>In this post, we will try and solve a little odd sum function that when is not satisfied will wait for the rest of the arguments you forgot to supply.</p><h4><span id="The_continues_sum_function"></span>The continues sum function<span></span></h4><p>Write a function that will add numbers as the following:</p><pre><code>sum(2,6); // 8
sum(3)(5); //8
sum(6,9,5); // 20
</code></pre><p>The first line seems easy just add two numbers, but wait‚Ä¶ the second line doesn‚Äôt look that obvious, and how come the third line sums up three numbers all of a sudden?</p><p>The first thing I recommend in this phase is ‚Äì just to stop‚Ä¶ don‚Äôt rush, make sure you understand exactly what you are requested to do in this task. Start by asking as many questions as you can, then write more examples, and only then move to the write code phase.</p><h4><span id="Questions_that_should_be_asked_before_starting"></span>Questions  that should be asked before starting<span></span></h4><ul><li>How many parameters does this function handle? 1- 3 or more?</li><li>Does it have some kind of memory mechanism for the last result?</li><li>Can it handle an unknown number of parameters?</li><li>Can you give me more examples?</li></ul><p>One you have answers to all of these questions you are ready to go!</p><ul><li>It can handle an unknown number.</li><li>Seems like it does.</li><li>Yes.</li><li>sum(1,2,3,4,5) // 15</li></ul><p>Ok‚Ä¶ seems like we are good to start.</p><p><a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/schittscreek-schitts-creek-605-LPB950a64mBWy7G72n" target="_blank" rel="noopener">via GIPHY</a></p><h4><span id="Always_start_from_a_simple_working_solution"></span>Always start from a simple working solution <span></span></h4><p>Basically writing a sum function that handles two arguments is simple</p><pre><code>function sum(a,b){
  return a +b ;
}</code></pre><p>We can now handle two parameters, that‚Äôs a start‚Ä¶.now let‚Äôs try more. This can be achieved in a few ways such as <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Functions/arguments#:~:text=The%20arguments%20object%20is%20a,first%20entry's%20index%20at%200%20." target="_blank">The arguments variable</a>: In every function, you will get for free the arguments variable which is an array-like variable, storing all the parameters this function received. Why am I calling it an array-like and not just an array? Since it‚Äôs not a child of the Array object prototype, it has only the length, no other build-in functions that you are used to. If you wish to cast it to a regular array ‚Äì no problem:</p><pre><code>const arrayOfArguments = Array.from(arguments);</code></pre><p>Now you are free to use all the built-in array functions such as filter, map sort, and more‚Ä¶</p><h4><span id="Javascript_argument_destructuring"></span>Javascript argument destructuring<span></span></h4><p>In this case, I will prefer to use the <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Spread_syntax" target="_blank">spread operator</a>, which is much more elegant in my opinion.</p><pre><code>function sum(...addUs){
  ///
}</code></pre><p> How can we sum an array ‚Äì the  reduce method:</p><pre><code>function sum(...addUs){
  return addUs.reduce((lastValue,current)=&gt; lastValue + current,0)
}</code></pre><p>We are now supporting a const known number of parameters. Getting better by the iteration. Now comes the interesting part that seems like our function is chainable in the example ‚Äì meaning we can just invoke it again using the ‚Äú()‚Äù syntax. This means we will need to return some sort of a function to the user.</p><pre><code>function sum(...addUs){
 const res = addUs.reduce((lastValue,current)=&gt; lastValue + current,0)
 return function(...args) {
 }

}</code></pre><p>We are summing the values and returning a new function. If we look carefully at our example ‚Äì when our function gets only one argument it will pause the sum calculation and wait for the next argument. If it has what it needs it will fire away the calculation. Seems like its time for an if statement</p><pre><code>function sum(...addUs){
 const res = addUs.reduce((lastValue,current)=&gt; lastValue + current,0)
 return addUs.length &gt; 1 ? res : function(...args) {
 }

}</code></pre><h4><span id="Putting_it_all_together"></span>Putting it all together<span></span></h4><p> If our number of arguments satisfies us we can just return the current sum result. If not then we need to return a new function and hold for the next parameters to be added in the next invocation:</p><pre><code>function sum(...addUs){
 const res = addUs.reduce((lastValue,current)=&gt; lastValue + current,0)
 return addUs.length &gt; 1 ? res : function(...args) {
      return res + args.reduce((lastValue,current)=&gt; lastValue + current,0);
 }</code></pre><p>Its time to review all our example and check that they are all satisfied.</p><pre><code>sum(2,6); // 8 check
sum(3)(5); //8 check
sum(6,9,5); // 20 check
sum(3)(5,5); 13 check</code></pre><p><a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/borat-great-success-a0h7sAqON67nO" target="_blank" rel="noopener">via GIPHY</a></p><p>Please share your thoughts and make sure you check our getting ready for the <a href="https://www.talkinghightech.com/en/category/javascript-interview/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">interview series</a>. Best of luck!</p></div></div>
